  whatItMeans: {
    en: "An ACD is a rare thing in criminal practice: a disposition that leaves the defendant with no criminal record and no admission of guilt. The statutory basis is Criminal Procedure Law § 170.55. The court adjourns the case for a set period; if the defendant stays out of trouble, the case is dismissed and the record sealed.\n\nHow it happens procedurally. The ACD is usually negotiated between the prosecutor and defense counsel, then presented to the court at arraignment or a later appearance. The court can grant an ACD on the motion of either side with the other side's consent, or on the court's own motion with both sides' consent. The court sets the adjournment period — up to 6 months for most cases, up to 12 months for marijuana and family offense cases. The court can attach conditions. The defendant complies during the adjournment. At the end of the period, the case is dismissed and sealed automatically, no further hearing needed.\n\nSealing under Criminal Procedure Law § 160.50. A dismissed ACD case is sealed. The arrest and the charge do not appear on most background checks. For most employment, housing, and licensing purposes, the defendant can truthfully answer 'no' to 'have you been convicted of a crime' — there is no conviction. Executive Law 296(16) makes it illegal for most employers to ask about or use a sealed arrest. Some databases retain access (law enforcement, certain licensing boards, federal security clearances), but the everyday background check does not see the case.\n\nConditions. The court often attaches conditions to the ACD. Common ones: community service (usually 20 to 100 hours), completion of a specific program (drug counseling, anger management, shoplifter intervention), no new arrests, no contact with the victim, staying away from specific locations, restitution to a victim, or participation in mediation. Conditions have to be lawful and not unduly onerous; defense counsel can push back on conditions that do not fit the case.\n\nExtended periods. The 12-month adjournment applies to marijuana cases (pre-MRTA framework, now largely obsolete since cannabis was decriminalized) and to family offense cases. Family offense ACDs include victim-safety conditions.\n\nRestitution. The court can require restitution as a condition. Failure to pay can be grounds to revoke the ACD. Restitution is common in petit larceny cases — the return of the item or payment of its value.\n\nViolation during the adjournment. If the defendant is rearrested, violates a condition, or fails to pay restitution, the prosecutor can apply to restore the case to the calendar. The court revokes the ACD and the case proceeds as if it had not been granted. The defendant is entitled to notice and a hearing on the alleged violation.\n\nWhat does not qualify. Felony cases are not eligible for ACD. Other diversion paths — Judicial Diversion under CPL Article 216, drug treatment court, problem-solving courts, and youthful offender status — apply to felony matters. Violent offenses and cases with serious harm usually do not receive an ACD. Repeat offenders with significant prior records also rarely get offered one.\n\nConditional discharge vs ACD. A conditional discharge is a conviction after a guilty plea. An ACD is not a conviction. Both carry conditions, but the no-conviction status of an ACD is the key difference — especially for immigration, licensing, and employment purposes.\n\nImmigration advantages. An ACD is generally not a 'conviction' under federal immigration law. A guilty plea or a conviction can trigger removability; an ACD does not. This makes ACD negotiation critical for non-citizen defendants. The U.S. Supreme Court's decision in Padilla v. Kentucky requires defense counsel to advise non-citizen defendants about immigration consequences, and counsel should evaluate ACD specifically in that light.\n\nTiming. The ACD has to be granted before the defendant pleads guilty or the trial starts. An ACD cannot be granted after conviction.\n\nFees. The ACD itself has no court fee, but any course or program attached as a condition may cost money. Fee waivers are available for indigent defendants.\n\nDisclosure after sealing. The general rule: a sealed case can be answered 'no' on 'have you been convicted' questions. Some applications specifically ask about 'arrests' — rare, but when it happens, consulting counsel is the right move. Federal employment and security clearances see a different set of records and may see the case even after sealing."
  },

